Author-Name: Zhongquan Zhou 
Author-Workplace-Name: Washington University in Saint Louis and the Wharton Center for Quantitative Finance 
Title: An Equilibrium Analysis of Hedging with Liquidity Constraints, Speculation, and Government Price Subsidy in a Commodity Market 
Abstract:
 We develop a simple commodity model to analyze (i) the effects of hedging
 with liquidity constraints, due to producers' inability to bear unlimited
 trading losses, (ii) the role of speculation in the process of risk
 allocation between consumers and producers, and (iii) the equilibrium
 implications of government price subsidies to the producers. We find that
 (1) liquidity constraints can cause futures prices to exhibit mean
 reversion, which then makes speculation profitable; (2) speculation tends
 to make futures price volatility an increasing function of futures price;
 and (3) government price subsidy, if actively hedged by the producers,
 serves to lower the futures risk premium and reduce futures volatility. Copyright The American Finance Association 1998. 
